===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*ǵeh₂r-}}
From earlier {{m|en|sloggorne}}, {{m|en|slughorne}}, {{m|en|slughorn|t=battle cry}}, borrowed from {{bor|en|gd|sluagh-ghairm|t=battle cry}}, from {{der|en|sga|slúag}}, {{m|sga|slóg|t=army; (''by extension'') assembly, crowd}} + {{m|sga|gairm|t=a call, cry}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=182013|date=1912|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref> {{m|sga||Slóg}} is derived from {{der|en|cel-pro|*slougos|t=army, troop}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*slowgʰos}}, {{m|ine-pro|*slowgos|t=entourage}}; and {{m|sga||gairm}} from {{der|en|cel-pro|*garman-}}, {{m|cel-pro|*garrman-|t=a call, shout}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*ǵeh₂r-|t=to call, shout}}. The English word is cognate with {{cog|la|garriō|t=to chatter, prattle}}, {{cog|ang|caru|t=anxiety, care, worry; grief, sorrow}}.

